<p><b>Thor Heyerdahl</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1914-10-06"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="10-06"><a href="/wiki/October_6" title="October 6">October 6</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1914" title="1914">1914</a></span> <a href="/wiki/Larvik" title="Larvik">Larvik</a>, <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="2002-04-18"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="04-18"><a href="/wiki/April_18" title="April 18">April 18</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/2002" title="2002">2002</a></span> <a href="/wiki/Colla_Micheri" title="Colla Micheri">Colla Micheri</a>, <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italy</a>) was a <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norwegian</a> <a href="/wiki/Ethnographer" title="Ethnographer" class="mw-redirect">ethnographer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Adventurer" title="Adventurer">adventurer</a> with a scientific background in <a href="/wiki/Zoology" title="Zoology">zoology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Geography" title="Geography">geography</a>. Heyerdahl became famous for his <i><a href="/wiki/Kon-Tiki" title="Kon-Tiki">Kon-Tiki</a></i> expedition, in which he sailed 4,300 miles (8,000 km) by raft from <a href="/wiki/South_America" title="South America">South America</a> to the <a href="/wiki/Tuamotu_Islands" title="Tuamotu Islands" class="mw-redirect">Tuamotu Islands</a>.</p>
